<h2 id="installation">Installation</h2>

<p>There are three ways to get access to these components and template. The most direct way is to <a href="http://github.com/dannyalright/contextkit/tree/master/origami/ContextKit">download the ready-to-go files</a> and riff from them. For more extensibility, follow either of the following:</p>

<h3 id="download-the-components-and-add-to-your-patch-library">Download the components and add to your Patch Library</h3>

<p><a href="http://github.com/dannyalright/contextkit/tree/master/origami/ContextKit">Download a ready-to-go file</a> and open into Origami. Right-click on the component and then click <em>Add to User Patch Libraryâ€¦</em>.</p>

<!-- Wrapping in div necessary to avoid Markdown rendering as <code> -->
<div class="media">
   
  <!-- Host images locally by default -->
  <img data-src="/assets/posts/2017-08-17-contextkit-for-origami/add-to-patch-library.jpg" />
   
</div>

<p>Next time you click on the New Layer button (+), you should see the component appear. This approach is good for quick-yet-global access across documents.</p>

<h3 id="download-the-system-and-open-in-origami">Download the system and open in Origami</h3>

<p>This is my recommended approach if you plan to use these extensively. <a href="http://github.com/dannyalright/contextkit/tree/master/origami">Clone or download the ComponentKit system</a> and open in Origami Studio. If you clone the repository, and choose <em>Install from Current Location</em>, the components can be updated automatically<sup id="fnref:githubsync"><a href="#fn:githubsync" class="footnote">1</a></sup>.</p>

<!-- Wrapping in div necessary to avoid Markdown rendering as <code> -->
<div class="media">
  
  <figure>
    
    <!-- Host images locally by default -->
    <img data-src="/assets/posts/2017-08-17-contextkit-for-origami/install-system.jpg" alt="Installing the ContextKit system in Origami Studio." />
    

    <figcaption>
      <!-- Caption links that are at the start of the caption -->
      
      Installing the ContextKit system in Origami Studio.

      <!-- Caption links that are at the end of the caption -->
      
    </figcaption>
  </figure>
  
</div>

<p>Next time you click on the New Layer button (+), you should see all the components appear.</p>

<h2 id="extending-to-android-and-framer">Extending to Android and Framer</h2>

<p>Iâ€™ve done the bare minimum to validate whether ContextKit is actually useful; a handful of iOS-only components, only for Origami. If these prove useful, I plan to extend ContextKit to include Android, more entry-points, and at least Framer.</p>

<h2 id="ios-10--11">iOS 10 â†’ 11</h2>

<p>The current animation and visual styles are modeled from the latest iOS 11 Beta. There are some inevitable inconsistencies that will be ironed out as iOS 11 matures and releases publicly this September-ish.</p>

